2.Chunking :

   Dividing documents into smaller chunks

Fixed chunking

chunk_size = 500

overlap = 50

Chunking is one of the most critical parts of RAG.

Bad chunking → bad retrieval → bad answers.

These are the 6 strategies used in modern RAG systems.

    1. Fixed Chunking
    
    Simplest method.
    
    Documents are split into fixed character or token length.
    
    Example:
    
    chunk_size = 500
    chunk_overlap = 50
    
    Advantages:

    simple
    
    fast
    
    Disadvantages:
    
    may break sentences or meaning.
    
    2. Recursive Chunking
    
    This is the most common strategy used in LangChain.
    
    LangChain uses RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter.
    
    It splits text hierarchically:
    
    Paragraph
      ↓
      Sentence
      ↓
      Words
      
      This preserves semantic meaning better than fixed chunking.
      
      3. Semantic Chunking
      
      Chunks are created based on meaning, not length.
      
      Example process:
      
        Sentence embeddings
        ↓
        Similarity detection
        ↓
        Group related sentences
        
        Advantages:
        
        preserves context
        
        improves retrieval accuracy
        
        Used in advanced RAG systems.
        
        4. Token-Based Chunking

        Chunks are created based on token limits of the LLM.
        
        Example:
        
        chunk_size = 256 tokens
        
        Useful when models have strict context windows.
        
        5. Sliding Window Chunking
        
        Chunks overlap with previous chunks.

        Example:
        
        Chunk 1 : tokens 1–500
        Chunk 2 : tokens 450–950
        Chunk 3 : tokens 900–1400
        
        Advantages:
        
        preserves context across boundaries
        
        reduces lost information

      6. Structure-Based Chunking
      
      Documents are split based on document structure.
      
      Example:
      
      Title
      Section
      Paragraph
      Bullet points
      
      Used in:
      
      research papers
      
      legal documents


